{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/2019/03/21/blender-tutorial-7-materials/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p><em>In this new post of the series Blender tutorial I will talk about materials.</em></p>\n<hr>\n<p>In the <a href=\"/2018/10/18/blender-tutorial-6-outliner-layers-groups-hierarchies-scenes/\">previous post of the series \"Blender tutorial\"</a>\nwe talked about the outliner, layers, groups and hierarchies in Blender. In this post we will start to add some details\nto our models by learning how to use <strong>materials</strong>.<br>\nTo set a material on an object we can select the material tab from the properties panel, and the press the new button.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/2bbf0/blender-create-material.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.50877192982456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"blender create material\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/0470c/blender-create-material.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/6c669/blender-create-material.jpg 285w,\n/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/882a4/blender-create-material.jpg 570w,\n/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/0470c/blender-create-material.jpg 1140w,\n/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/2bbf0/blender-create-material.jpg 1496w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">blender create material</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>After creating we material a new list of option to customize it appears. We have the possibility to change the\nmaterial's name. We can select the material type. The available options are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Surface</em>, render object as a surface</li>\n<li><em>Wire</em>, render the edges of faces as wires</li>\n<li><em>Volume</em>, render object as a volume</li>\n<li><em>Halo</em>, render object as halo particles</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Most of the time (9/10 times) we will use the surface types. The other are for special effects we will see in the\nfuture. Then we have other options to customize the main components of the material. The definitions given below of\nthese components are from an artist point of view. If you're interested to know the details on the computer graphics\nside, you can have a look\nat <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_graphics_lighting\" title=\"Lighting computer graphics\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">this documentation</a>\n(on the web you can find plenty of resources about this topic). So the main material components are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>diffuse</em>, the main color of the objects</li>\n<li><em>specular</em>, that define the highlights</li>\n<li><em>shading</em>, that defines the type light emission of the material, the ambient component that empirically models the\nresult of indirect lighting and other options (that we will see in details later)</li>\n<li><em>transparency</em></li>\n<li><em>mirror</em></li>\n<li><em>subsurface scattering</em>, to model material in which light will enter on a point of the surface and will exit from\nanother one. This component is useful to model translucency effects.</li>\n<li><em>strand</em>, to model hair particles</li>\n<li><em>shadows</em></li>\n<li><em>other options</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/ab52d1c0d3d907c58e8a5fd4d91dd657/f8188/blender-material-panel.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.50877192982456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"The material panel\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/ab52d1c0d3d907c58e8a5fd4d91dd657/0470c/blender-material-panel.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/ab52d1c0d3d907c58e8a5fd4d91dd657/6c669/blender-material-panel.jpg 285w,\n/static/ab52d1c0d3d907c58e8a5fd4d91dd657/882a4/blender-material-panel.jpg 570w,\n/static/ab52d1c0d3d907c58e8a5fd4d91dd657/0470c/blender-material-panel.jpg 1140w,\n/static/ab52d1c0d3d907c58e8a5fd4d91dd657/f8188/blender-material-panel.jpg 1494w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The material panel</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>We can assign multiple material to the same objects. To do it we just need to :</p>\n<ul>\n<li>add a new material slot using the plus button</li>\n<li>select (in edit mode) the part of the object to which we want to apply the material and click the assign button</li>\n</ul>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/4deeba11dbc07b385098b0c096d1d605/f8188/blender-multiple-material.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.50877192982456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"It is possible to assign multiple material to the same objects\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/4deeba11dbc07b385098b0c096d1d605/0470c/blender-multiple-material.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/4deeba11dbc07b385098b0c096d1d605/6c669/blender-multiple-material.jpg 285w,\n/static/4deeba11dbc07b385098b0c096d1d605/882a4/blender-multiple-material.jpg 570w,\n/static/4deeba11dbc07b385098b0c096d1d605/0470c/blender-multiple-material.jpg 1140w,\n/static/4deeba11dbc07b385098b0c096d1d605/f8188/blender-multiple-material.jpg 1494w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">It is possible to assign multiple material to the same objects</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Now let's star to have a deeper look at the <strong>diffuse component</strong>. As we said before, the diffuse component defines the\nmain color of our object. The default shader applied to it is the lambert shader. Lambertian is an ideal diffuse\nreflection that ideally reflect equally the light in all direction. We have also the possibility to choose one of the\nother shaders:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Oren-Nayar</em>, a shader that models also the roughness of the surface</li>\n<li><em>Toon shading</em>, a shader with hard light cutting off</li>\n<li><em>Minnaert</em>, a shader with rim-light effects (useful when you need this effects but you don't wont to place a light\nbehind the object)</li>\n<li><em>Fresnel</em>, a shader that also inverts specularity of the objects.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>All the diffuse shader types have an intensity parameter to adjust their contribution to the final look of the objects.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/bdb291a0b62160c57086a67125a5c5ab/99781/blender-material-diffuse-component.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.859649122807014%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"The material diffuse component\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/bdb291a0b62160c57086a67125a5c5ab/0470c/blender-material-diffuse-component.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/bdb291a0b62160c57086a67125a5c5ab/6c669/blender-material-diffuse-component.jpg 285w,\n/static/bdb291a0b62160c57086a67125a5c5ab/882a4/blender-material-diffuse-component.jpg 570w,\n/static/bdb291a0b62160c57086a67125a5c5ab/0470c/blender-material-diffuse-component.jpg 1140w,\n/static/bdb291a0b62160c57086a67125a5c5ab/99781/blender-material-diffuse-component.jpg 1497w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The material diffuse component</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>After the diffuse component there's the <strong>specular component</strong>. This component is used to represent the\nhighlights/shininess of the surface. We can select the color as for the diffuse shader. We also have again a intensity\nparameter to tweak the contribution of the specular component to the final material appearance. There's a list of shader\nwe can choose from:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>cook-torrance</em></li>\n<li><em>phong</em></li>\n<li><em>blinn-phong</em></li>\n<li><em>toon</em></li>\n<li><em>wardiso</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/77b5f8773be4aae5703cc99c8f99c418/2bbf0/blender-material-specular-component.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.50877192982456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"The material specular component\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/77b5f8773be4aae5703cc99c8f99c418/0470c/blender-material-specular-component.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/77b5f8773be4aae5703cc99c8f99c418/6c669/blender-material-specular-component.jpg 285w,\n/static/77b5f8773be4aae5703cc99c8f99c418/882a4/blender-material-specular-component.jpg 570w,\n/static/77b5f8773be4aae5703cc99c8f99c418/0470c/blender-material-specular-component.jpg 1140w,\n/static/77b5f8773be4aae5703cc99c8f99c418/2bbf0/blender-material-specular-component.jpg 1496w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The material specular component</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>For both the diffuse and specular component we have also the <strong>ramp option</strong>. With this option it is possible to apply\ngradient on the surface. The ramp option could be useful to add a little bit more pop to the material final look. The\nstarting values for ramp contains two color, but we can add as many intermediate points as we want.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/c8b1e5ae01063ecc503e9ef1f04ea6e5/2bbf0/blender-ramp-material.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.50877192982456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"The ramp material\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/c8b1e5ae01063ecc503e9ef1f04ea6e5/0470c/blender-ramp-material.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/c8b1e5ae01063ecc503e9ef1f04ea6e5/6c669/blender-ramp-material.jpg 285w,\n/static/c8b1e5ae01063ecc503e9ef1f04ea6e5/882a4/blender-ramp-material.jpg 570w,\n/static/c8b1e5ae01063ecc503e9ef1f04ea6e5/0470c/blender-ramp-material.jpg 1140w,\n/static/c8b1e5ae01063ecc503e9ef1f04ea6e5/2bbf0/blender-ramp-material.jpg 1496w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The ramp material</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>We have also some shading option that we can use to set other to surface components. In particular we can set the\nambient and emit components using the slider contained in this section. We can also completely turn off the shader by\nusing the shadeless option, or using the tangent shading option to create tangent specular highlights.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/8c66fbdf645843e0409eccb726176c94/2bbf0/blender-shading-options.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.859649122807014%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Shading options\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/8c66fbdf645843e0409eccb726176c94/0470c/blender-shading-options.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/8c66fbdf645843e0409eccb726176c94/6c669/blender-shading-options.jpg 285w,\n/static/8c66fbdf645843e0409eccb726176c94/882a4/blender-shading-options.jpg 570w,\n/static/8c66fbdf645843e0409eccb726176c94/0470c/blender-shading-options.jpg 1140w,\n/static/8c66fbdf645843e0409eccb726176c94/2bbf0/blender-shading-options.jpg 1496w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Shading options</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Now we will take a look at how we can create <strong>reflective material</strong>. To create a reflective material we can activate\nthe Mirror component. We have some options to customize the final result of our reflection:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>reflectivity</em>, that let us customize the amount of reflection</li>\n<li><em>fresnel</em>, that let us customize the amount of reflection at grazing incidence</li>\n<li><em>depth</em>, the maximum number of reflection bounce</li>\n<li><em>max dist</em>, the maximum distance of object to be reflected</li>\n<li><em>gloss</em>, to setup a glossy reflection effect</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Remember that the mirror material result is visible only in the final render view.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/808a43c118c90c46c7326c58e7f90b84/e984e/blender-reflection.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.50877192982456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"The mirror material useful to implement reflection\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/808a43c118c90c46c7326c58e7f90b84/0470c/blender-reflection.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/808a43c118c90c46c7326c58e7f90b84/6c669/blender-reflection.jpg 285w,\n/static/808a43c118c90c46c7326c58e7f90b84/882a4/blender-reflection.jpg 570w,\n/static/808a43c118c90c46c7326c58e7f90b84/0470c/blender-reflection.jpg 1140w,\n/static/808a43c118c90c46c7326c58e7f90b84/e984e/blender-reflection.jpg 1495w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The mirror material useful to implement reflection</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>After mirror material we can take a look at the <strong>transparency component</strong>. To make a transparent material we have to\nactivate this component. There are 3 option:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>z transparency</em>, a simple transparency without refraction or any other sort of realistic features</li>\n<li><em>mask</em>, a simple masks for the Background. It uses the alpha channel to mix the color of each pixel on the active\nobject plane with the color of the corresponding background pixel, according to the alpha channel of the pixel</li>\n<li><em>raytrace</em>, a realistic transparency configurable with Index Of Refraction (IOR) and other parameters.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/cfa5ed5a0391c7b2eca176ddea96f10b/f8188/blender-transparency.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.50877192982456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"The transparency component\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/cfa5ed5a0391c7b2eca176ddea96f10b/0470c/blender-transparency.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/cfa5ed5a0391c7b2eca176ddea96f10b/6c669/blender-transparency.jpg 285w,\n/static/cfa5ed5a0391c7b2eca176ddea96f10b/882a4/blender-transparency.jpg 570w,\n/static/cfa5ed5a0391c7b2eca176ddea96f10b/0470c/blender-transparency.jpg 1140w,\n/static/cfa5ed5a0391c7b2eca176ddea96f10b/f8188/blender-transparency.jpg 1494w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">The transparency component</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Last but not least we have <strong>subsurface scattering</strong>. As reported\non <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subsurface_scattering\" title=\"Subsurface scattering\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">wikipedia</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Subsurface scattering is a mechanism of light transport in which light penetrates the surface of a translucent object, is scattered by interacting with the material, and exits the surface at a different point</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>We have some parameter to modify the final result of this component:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>index of refraction</em></li>\n<li><em>scale</em>, to determine how deep the light goes</li>\n<li><em>RGB radius</em>, that is a color used to blur</li>\n<li><em>scattering weights</em>, to tweak if the effects it is more on front then on the back</li>\n<li><em>blend</em></li>\n</ul>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 1140px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/8ff5e71981460e265696914d422f0980/e984e/blender-subsurface-scattering.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 63.50877192982456%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Subsurface scattering\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/8ff5e71981460e265696914d422f0980/0470c/blender-subsurface-scattering.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/8ff5e71981460e265696914d422f0980/6c669/blender-subsurface-scattering.jpg 285w,\n/static/8ff5e71981460e265696914d422f0980/882a4/blender-subsurface-scattering.jpg 570w,\n/static/8ff5e71981460e265696914d422f0980/0470c/blender-subsurface-scattering.jpg 1140w,\n/static/8ff5e71981460e265696914d422f0980/e984e/blender-subsurface-scattering.jpg 1495w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1140px) 100vw, 1140px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Subsurface scattering</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>In the next post we will talk about textures.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Blender tutorial: materials","comments":true,"authors":["fabrizio_duroni"],"tags":["computer graphics","blender"],"date":"21 Mar 2019","description":"In this new post of the series Blender tutorial I will talk about materials.","math":false,"image":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fullWidth","backgroundColor":"#484848","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/254f0/blender-create-material.jpg","srcSet":"/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/20a1e/blender-create-material.jpg 750w,\n/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/55aa4/blender-create-material.jpg 1080w,\n/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/641bb/blender-create-material.jpg 1366w,\n/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/254f0/blender-create-material.jpg 1496w","sizes":"100vw"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/b6fab/blender-create-material.webp 750w,\n/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/0034c/blender-create-material.webp 1080w,\n/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/7687b/blender-create-material.webp 1366w,\n/static/a5aeee68faf7b7bbeeb7db54f0c9d341/3c524/blender-create-material.webp 1496w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"100vw"}]},"width":1,"height":0.6356951871657754}}}},"fields":{"slug":"/2019/03/21/blender-tutorial-7-materials/","readingTime":{"text":"6 min read"}}},"site":{"siteMetadata":{"author":"Fabrizio Duroni"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/2019/03/21/blender-tutorial-7-materials/"}},"staticQueryHashes":["2055070849","3076394108","379746230","4028829600"],"slicesMap":{}}